Passengers of the Australian airlines will need and to switch off further the tablets and smartphones during take off and landing, despite measures in the USA for mitigation of the rules concerning these devices.
The Federal Aviation Administration of the USA allowed the American carriers to change the procedures so that passengers could read electronic books, watch video or play games on the devices during take off and landing provided that those will remain in "The flight mode".
Passengers can already do it during the main part of flight, but many irritates that they have no access to the electronic books during take off and landing.
The Australian carriers consider this decision which demanded from the American airlines to carry out a huge number of work for compliance to new requirements, but specified that they do not plan to change the procedures in the near future.
In Management of safety of flights of civil aviation also noted that they consider this application, but emphasized that restrictions on use of electronic devices in critical phases of flight still ​​ work in Australia.
"Management of safety of flights of civil aviation has no the special rules regulating use of electronic devices in planes" now — it declared.
The matter is regulated by rules which demand from air carriers to provide safety maintenance at any time, and from passengers — to follow safety rules about which they are reported by crew members.
The Virgin company which already discussed with Management of safety of flights of civil aviation expansion of use onboard the entertaining system with Wi-Fi, was not against changes, but declared that it will follow indications of the regulator.
"We would welcome consideration by Management of safety of flights of civil aviation of a question of permission of use of electronic devices because we really think that it will improve quality of customer service now when it (onboard wireless entertaining system) is by our planes" — the press secretary told.
Qantas declared that will adhere to the rules existing at the moment.
"Our present policy consists that electronic devices cannot be used during take off and landing, and soon we do not plan it to change" — she declared.
The resolution FAU extends on the American airlines.
Nevertheless we are always interested in regulatory changes which could bring benefit to passengers, and we, certainly, will attentively study the solution of FAU and reason, caused it.
For carriers of the USA influence of the resolution will vary from airline to airline and will depend on age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove that their planes possess resistance to a radio noise from mobile devices, and also to reconsider grants, training materials, norms on transportation of hand luggage and the instruction for passengers.
"After the airline will check and will confirm a noise stability of the fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, easy electronic devices, such as tablets, electronic books and smartphones, at any height" — declared FAU.
