Scientists shed light how the movements of a tail of a dog are connected with her mood.
Earlier researches showed that happy dogs wag a tail to the right side (from the point of view of a dog) while alarmed dogs wag with a tail mainly to the left side.
But now scientists say that other representatives of family of the psovy can notice these subtle differences in wagging by a tail and react to them.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, the neurobiologist from Trentsky university, speaks: "It is well known that at people the left and right parties of a brain differently participate in formation of pobuditel who cause positive or negative emotions".
Here we tried to look at it and at other types.
He added that the same as at the person, at dogs the right part of a brain controls the left side of a body and vice versa, and two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more how dogs react to versatile povilivaniye of tails of other dogs, researchers watched animals when they watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the frequency of heartbeat of animals and analyzed their behavior.
Possibly, we will understand already soon why their tails sometimes go to one party, and sometimes — in another
Professor Vallortigara told: "We showed to dogs of video with dogs — either naturalistic versions, or a silhouette to get rid of any other distorting factors, and we could manipulate the movement of a tail and direct a tail more to the left or to the right".
When animals saw that for the rest nothing the expressing dog moved a tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging a tail), they remained absolutely weakened.
But when they noticed that the tail inclined mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging a tail), their heartbeat became frequent and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara told that he does not think that dogs intentionally communicated with each other with the help of these movements.
Actually he considers that dogs learned from the experience, about what movements they should worry, and about what — no.
He notices: "If there are some meetings with other dogs and often wagging of their tail in one party are connected with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, the dog reacts on the basis of this experience".
Researchers say that these results can yield to owners, veterinarians and trainers deeper understanding of emotions of the animal.
The expert in the field of behavior of dogs John Bradshaw, the invited research associate at veterinary school of University of Bristol, told that it was not the first research for check of, whether the left and right parties have value for dogs.
Last year the group of scientists of university of the Lincoln found out that dogs turn the heads to the left if look at an aggressive dog, and to the right if look at a happy dog.
And in other scientific work of university of the Victoria in Canada it reported: "Dogs approached a thicket a dog robot when wagging of her tail went to the left, but not to the right instead of becoming alarmed — opposite behavior in relation to the Italian research".
He told that distinctions could be because dogs in various researches not completely perceived animals in movies or dogs robots as dogs.
There could be useful a research of how dogs react to the real dogs, he explained.
"While on various mammals there are enough certificates of that two hemispheres of a brain are used for various purposes, many details still it is necessary to specify, and dogs not an exception" — he told.
However, considering that ease with which their behavior probably can be registered already soon we will understand why their tails sometimes go to one party, and sometimes — in another.
