Trip on dirt, the rivers and the jungle for rendering free medical care
Doctor George Bvelle provides free medical care in rural areas in Cameroon
Bvelle and his team carry out almost every weekend, accepting hundreds of patients
In this West African country of doctors there is not a lot of — only one on 5000 people
Vote here or via your mobile device
Doctor George Bvelle — one of 10 main heroes of CNN of 2013.
You can vote for it or for any of other 10 main characters that he became the Hero of year of CNN.
This person will receive $250 000 for continuation of the outstanding work.
During 21 year George Bvelle saw how his father was restored to life and again fell into an unconsciousness, wandering on hospitals which were not equipped properly to help it.
Dzhamef Bvelle was traumatized in road accident in 1981 near Yaounde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first at it the hand was only broken, but the arisen infection extended on a brain and caused a hematoma which reminded of itself until the end of life.
"In Cameroon there were no neurosurgeons — George Bvelle told.
If we had money, we would take out it from Cameroon.
Instead of this Bvelle accompanied for years the father in the crowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment which they could receive.
"It is hard — Bvelle told.
— You can leave the house in the 5th mornings, come running in hospital to be the first, but you not the first.
There is a lot of patients.
Some can die because they should wait.
The situation not strongly changed since the father Bvelle died in 2002.
According to World Health Organization, in Cameroon only one doctor on 5000 people.
For comparison, a ratio in the United States — one doctor on 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could address to the doctor, it would be too expensive for much of them.
Two of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three quarters of expenses on health care in it are private.
"Their only problem is poverty — Bvelle told.
— And because of poverty they cannot enjoy the life".
Seeing sufferings of the father and his very many compatriots, Bvelle was filled determination something with it to make.
Last year doctor George Bvelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free operations.
He became a doctor and works as the vascular surgeon in the Central hospital Yaounde.
It also founded ASCOVIME non-profit organization which will organize trips to rural areas on days off for providing free medical care.
Since 2008 it and its group of volunteers gave help of nearly 32 000 people.
Nearly an every Friday it and to 30 people jam in vans, tie medical belongings to roofs and go on a cross-country terrain to visit the villages needing the help.
Not always they are accompanied by good luck.
More than once they had to push cars through the rivers and dirt.
But when they come, them meet, as real heroes: it is a holiday with songs and dances and the best rooms what locals can only offer.
The free medical care in these villages really is a reason for a holiday, and Bvelle with his wide smile and boundless energy more than is happy to join fun.
The next morning the crew starts accepting hundreds of patients.
"We accept 500 people on each trip" — Bvelle told.
They come with all the district in a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these clinics of the day off provides various medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and diseases, sexually transmitted.
Others can receive crutches, the offered points or free birth certificates — the documents necessary for school which many poor families simply are not able to afford.
In the evenings the crew performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are, as a rule, performed in the building of school, municipality or in the house; after procedure patients get up and go to a postoperative zone to release a place for the following person.
Using the generator for publicizing of operational and sanitary processing of the equipment, Bvelle and his volunteers work till early morning of Sunday.
It is excessive speed, but rural musicians usually help to maintain commitment of crew.
"They all night long beat the drum that we were awake and continued to work" — Bvelle told.
On Sunday members of crew go back to the city, tired, but proud of the work.
This group consisting of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students performed 700 free operations for last year, and they know that their help can have huge value for those to whom they help.
One person explained that the free operation on treatment of hernia received by him will allow it to work again.
"It will change the future for me and my family" — the man told.
In addition to these clinical receptions in days off and work in hospital as the surgeon Bvelle also works at the nights in private medical clinics round Yaounde.
This second work, according to him, provides 60% of financing of its non-profit organization; other means become covered at the expense of private donations.
"I do not even know when he sleeps" — Cathie O'Malley, the medical student of the second year of Drekselsky university in Philadelphia, the volunteer in group Bvelle told.
He always or in hospital, or tries to earn money for the organization that it was possible to continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses, such as O'Malley, coming from the USA and Europe to join Bvella in realization of his tasks, is opportunity of practice which they never had at home.
"We had an opportunity to assist on operations where we helped to delete spots of blood or to hold tools for doctor Bvelle" — O'Malley told.
Being the student second-year student, you would never receive such opportunity in America.
Students volunteers usually pay the journey to Cameroon, often arriving with the offered medicines.
But on arrival in Yaounde their food, transport and training pays by Bvelle.
"He is a hero, undoubtedly" — O'Malley told.
It gives the life of this organization, and his desire to help people of Cameroon infinitely.
