Package of saving measures of $325 million for health care of Tasmania
The federal government insists that the package of saving measures of $325 million for the weakened health system of Tasmania will be added with severe conditions which guarantee that the government of staff will not spend means for nothing.
The federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek declared that the Commonwealth takes "urgent measures" to prevent the crisis caused by aging of the population of this island state, higher level of chronic diseases and restrictions of system.
The decision on financing within four years was made after consultations of the government with the independent deputy of Tasmania Andrew Wilkie.
"The government offered a package of the emergency saving measures which, we trust, will solve specific problems, facing staff" — Mrs. Plibersek declared today.
The package of $325 million in size includes $31 million for blitz campaign for planned operations.
2600 more operations, including orthopedic and operations on removal of a cataract, will help to overcome lag.
There is also money for the clinics accepting patients without making an appointment in Hobart and Launceston, for improvement of quality of leaving after a hospital, training of medical experts, security services of mental health and introduction of systems of personal electronic medical records in local hospitals.
"These investments will go on the ideas stated by the advanced doctors realization how it is better to help health system of Tasmania" — Mrs. Plibersek told.
The minister insisted that the government of Tasmania will work in the mode of the strict reporting and responsibility.
Staff will need to support the current levels of financing to receive funds of the Commonwealth, and monthly to report on where it spends these additional resources.
The commission from three people will be created to be convinced that staff provides services as it is possible more effectively and is more effective.
Mr. Wilkie declared today that $325 million will solve nothing, "if they are not followed by original reform which will put health system of Tasmania on steadier basis".
Nevertheless he praised the government for the answer to its request for the urgent help with which he for the first time addressed to the prime minister at the beginning of May.
"I hope that the package of the federal help will promote considerably to a conclusion of health system of this staff from critical condition" — Mr. Wilkie told.
According to the government of staff, these additional selective procedures substantially compensate recent reductions.
