Only a few hundreds of supporters gathered at the courthouse to welcome the new president, and, unlike a presidential pomp of times of Mubarak, the movement was stopped only for a short time to pass its motorcade on usually brisk road connecting the downtown to the southern suburbs.
Though Morsi derided as not charismatic "a spare wheel" of "Brothers", its personal prestige sharply grew from the moment of its victory and Friday performance in which he tried to present itself(himself) as the candidate not only Islamists, but also all those who wants to finish business of revolt of 2011 against authoritative Mubarak.
"Today Egypt is the civil, national, constitutional and modern state" — Morsi dressed in a blue business suit with a red tie, to judges in the hall sheathed by wooden panels where he took the oath told.
After Morsi went to Cairo university where he had to deliver the inaugural speech.
The formal reception with the army orchestra which executed a national anthem during which he stood at attention "quietly" was accorded to it.
There was a military figure field marshal Hussein Tantawi.
Its arrival was met by the slogan "Army and the People — One Hand" which was chanted by hundreds of audience in the main lecture hall of university.
The founded in 1908 as a stronghold of secular education, Cairo university in the 1970th years became a stronghold of Islamic student's groups.
Morsi took the symbolical oath on Friday on Tahrir Square where the revolt which finished authoritative board of Mubarak last year arose and promised to return powers of the president of which his position was deprived by the Council of War which accepted affairs from the overthrown leader.
But having agreed to take the official oath before court, but not before parliament as it is accepted, it carries out will of military, and it is a sign of that race for power will proceed.
