RBS discharges two currency traders
The royal bank of Scotland temporarily discharged of work of two traders in the division on currency transactions, according to information of two people familiar with this situation that is one more confirmation of that global check by regulators of alleged manipulations in the currency market promptly grows.
Some of the largest world banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, confirmed that they cooperate with regulators in the investigations connected with the world's largest financial market which daily turn makes $5,3 trillion.
These two traders will be the first employees of RBS discharged during the developed investigation which has something in common with the scandal connected with manipulations with an interbank rate of LIBOR.
Having refused to comment on discharges, the bank confirmed that this month it received requests for providing information from regulators.
"Our current investigation of this question proceeds, and we completely cooperate with FCA and other our regulators" — reported in bank two weeks ago.
Last month the informed persons told that RBS transferred records of e-mail and instant messages which received and the former trader, to regulator of Great Britain — to Management on control of financial activity (FCA) sent it.
This trader, Richard Asher, left RBS in 2010 and, as far as we know, it was granted leave at its current position of the head of the European spot currency auction in JPMorgan.
Rokhan Ramchandani, the head of the European spot auction in Citi, went on leave this week while Matt Gardiner, the former senior currency trader in Barclays and UBS, was discharged of work as Standard Chartered bank this week.
None of these traders were not accused of any violations.
The group of contacts of instant messages of Mr. Asher included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, according to the informed persons.
The UBS bank reported this week that it took measures against some employees after the Swiss Finma regulator told that he investigates alleged manipulations in the currency market in a number of the Swiss banks.
At least six regulators in the world — the European commission, Finma, antimonopoly authority of Switzerland Weko, FCA, the Ministry of Justice of the USA and Currency management of Hong Kong — consider statements that bankers entered arrangement for impact on the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse also began internal checks or received requests for providing information from regulators, persons, familiar with a situation, told.
Banks look through instant messages and e-mails for some years in search of cases of offenses.
News about checks stirred up traders in the field of activity which was in recent years one of the largest sources of the income of trade divisions of investment banks which this year, however, met difficulties in view of the fact that low volatility of currencies reduces favorable opportunities for dealers.
Some bankers tried to diminish gravity of a situation, saying that the extensive and highly liquid currency market cannot almost be manipulated, but the senior traders say that it is not always right.
According to the senior trader, despite the huge volume of the daily auction in the currency market, fragmentation of liquidity between various trade platforms and wider use of the internal platforms by banks means that "you can start having impact on the market for absolutely small price".
This news came on the same day when the Credit Suisse bank declared that dismissed one of traders of the department of the share auction of the London exchange this week after that caused losses of nearly 6 million dollars at the end of last year.
The bank immediately notified appropriate authorities and cooperates with the regulators.
"We are sure that the trader acted alone and that this question managed to be localized" — reported Credit Suisse.
