Two employees of YMCA are accused of sexual crimes even before charges against Johnathan Lord as the Royal commission knew
Two employees of YMCA NSW were accused of sexual crimes against children before promotion of charges in 2011 against the employee of institution on care of children in Karingbakh of Johnathan Lord, reported to the Royal commission on sexual violence over children.
But in an opening statement of the commission it was said that it "never dealt with cases of sexual violence over children in the organization".
The chief executive officer Philipp Hare was asked about one case when the worker of YMCA was accused of the crimes connected with a child pornography and about other case when the instructor of the sports hall in YMCA Caringbah Hall was condemned for sexual crimes against the children who were under its supervision in 1991.
Mr. Hare told Gale Ferness, to the lawyer giving help to the commission that he knew about the first case, but did not know about the second.
He recognized that YMCA in opening speech for the commission also allowed inaccuracy, claiming that "there were external checks of YMCA which recognized that YMCA is on safety of children in the forefront".
The presented commissions of the certificate say that YMCA was notified that it received the second since the end from four possible estimates by results of audit of the quality executed by Department of Education and communities in August of this year.
Mr. Hare who entered YMCA when he was 21 years old, recognized that it and the subordinate management allowed a miss, having employed the Lord, and also could not provide a clear understanding with the personnel of the obligations concerning the message on violations of a security policy of children.
Earlier this year the Lord was condemned for sexual crimes against 12 boys within two years of his work in YMCA.
He was imprisoned at least for six years.
But Mr. Hare rejected the assumption that corporate ethics of YMCA prevented employees to report about violations of the Lord in the sphere of safety of children.
Employees gave evidences that they observed violations, including that the Lord was alone with children, personally looked after them, put them to itself on knees, said that he loves one of them and allowed them to play the mobile phone.
Daniel Okvell which was under the direction of Lorda and asked to train it in protection of children because she was concerned by his behavior, testified that found Jackie Barnat, the guardianship manager over children of office of YMCA in Karingbakh which was the head Lorda, "very frightening and often remote".
The executive director told that he does not accept an explanation of employees that it was awkward to them to report about a situation to the higher heads.
More likely, according to him, their friendship with the Lord took away them from thought of need to report about him.
Mr. Hare told that he presented to council of YMCA of New South Wales the opinion that the lesson for the organization from "incident with Johnathan Lord" not "concerns providing information" from employees, and council agreed with it.
Mr. Hare declared that the decision to force employees to sign agreements on confidentiality soon after emergence of charges was made by the CEO of YMCA on guardianship over children Liam Wheatley.
He told that it was urged to prevent damage of proofs, but thus "were overzealous" and this decision badly realized.
YMCA of New South Wales was not the organization, safe for children, in operating time of Johnathan Lord in it during 2009-2011, the expert in problems of corruption of children professor Stephen Smolboun from Griffith University reported the commissions.
He told that there were "serious problems" at a set, selection, instructing, training of the personnel and control of it.
Hearings are postponed until December 20.
